WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.150 --> 00:00:02.400
- This is the brand new
Guinness World Record,

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:04.890
largest ever elephant
toothpaste foam experiment.

00:00:04.890 --> 00:00:07.380
In today's video, which is
partially sponsored by LastPass,

00:00:07.380 --> 00:00:08.730
I'm gonna walk you through everything

00:00:08.730 --> 00:00:10.770
we have to go through
to get to this point,

00:00:10.770 --> 00:00:12.660
as well as some really
cool side discoveries

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:15.780
we made in our hundreds of
hours of testing along the way.

00:00:15.780 --> 00:00:17.610
The main ingredient for
elephant's toothpaste

00:00:17.610 --> 00:00:19.020
is hydrogen peroxide.

00:00:19.020 --> 00:00:21.990
It's the same stuff you pour
on a scrape to disinfect it.

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:23.970
The thing is, the bonds
that hold the hydrogen

00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:25.830
and oxygen together are pretty weak.

00:00:25.830 --> 00:00:27.990
So if we poured some of this in here,

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:29.760
and just left it for a while,

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:32.100
it would keep releasing
oxygen and eventually,

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:33.480
you'd be left with just water.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:36.420
However, if you add a catalyst
like potassium iodide,

00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:39.549
you could make that slow
process happen almost instantly.

00:00:39.549 --> 00:00:41.520
(concoction hisses)

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:43.740
So that's cool, but we can
make it way more impressive

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:46.050
if we add one key ingredient, soap.

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:49.440
So if we pour this in and then
do everything else the same,

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:51.390
now when the oxygen is released,

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:54.450
the soap captures it,
creating bubbles and foam.

00:00:54.450 --> 00:00:56.070
And then finally, if
you do all that again,

00:00:56.070 --> 00:00:58.740
only now you add food
coloring and use a flask

00:00:58.740 --> 00:00:59.880
that tapers like this,

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:01.590
you can focus the expansion of foam

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:03.745
so it looks maximum awesome.

00:01:03.745 --> 00:01:06.412
(bright music)

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:11.190
So in order to fill a
pool with this stuff,

00:01:11.190 --> 00:01:12.750
I first got together with some friends,

00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:15.390
and we spent literally hundreds
of hours for a few weeks

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.010
running experiments to calculate

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:19.020
the best raw ingredient combinations

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:21.120
in addition to brainstorming
other cool things

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:21.990
we might do with it.

00:01:21.990 --> 00:01:23.580
And so before we attempted to shatter

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:24.570
the current world record,

00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:26.700
we had an end-of-summer party with my son

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:28.020
and a bunch of family friends

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:29.340
where we wanted to share with them

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:31.650
the coolest side discoveries
from our research.

00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:33.840
But first, in true end-of-summer fashion,

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:35.936
we had to knock out some
slip and slide kickball.

00:01:35.936 --> 00:01:38.519
(upbeat music)

00:01:45.907 --> 00:01:49.350
(upbeat music)

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:51.060
I planned to kick things
off by attacking them

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:52.950
with an elephant toothpaste gun we made

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:55.860
as revenge for when a bunch
of these same kids ambushed me

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:56.940
on a recent beach trip,

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:58.380
and then offered me some cookies

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:00.630
which were just six massive cockroaches.

00:02:00.630 --> 00:02:02.056
And I hate cockroaches.

00:02:02.056 --> 00:02:03.606
Shamoo! Get it off me!

00:02:03.606 --> 00:02:04.800
However, as part of our testing,

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:06.930
we discover the reaction
is highly exothermic,

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:09.060
which means it generates
heat as a byproduct.

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:09.930
If you watch it infrared,

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:11.400
you'll see the temperature
of the foam right

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:14.610
after the reaction can reach
almost 200 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:17.370
So, because I'm nice, I
shelved my revenge plans

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:19.680
and just demonstrated what
would've been their fate,

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:22.170
and told them to sit and
watch at a safe distance.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:23.823
And they listened, sort of.

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:28.880
And so now that we have their
attention, it was showtime.

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:31.974
- [Everyone] Three, two, one!

00:02:31.974 --> 00:02:32.807
- Go!

