actually make the bubbles.

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:21.093
Soap isn't part of the reaction.

00:06:23.134 --> 00:06:23.967
(motors whirring)

00:06:23.967 --> 00:06:25.350
Two more soap buckets.

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:30.350
Oh, as you can see, that
bucket's filling up real quick.

00:06:31.628 --> 00:06:32.850
(bright music)

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:35.643
So after a few final
touches, we were ready to go.

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:39.210
Three, two, one!

00:06:41.821 --> 00:06:42.990
Now before we cut the tarps,

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:44.700
I wanna point out I'm not a chemist.

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:46.140
With the physics and engineering problem,

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:48.450
I'm way more comfortable
understanding the parameters

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:50.760
and getting closer to the
final solution off the bat,

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:53.760
but chemistry is just little
molecules I can't see.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:55.530
And it feels a lot like trial and error

00:06:55.530 --> 00:06:58.560
without any guarantee it will
actually scale up predictably.

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:01.200
This was feeling like the
nightmare of the jello pool

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:02.100
